SIMPLE: enfilade
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enfilade
<hw>En`fi*lade"</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
<ets>enfiler</ets> to thread, go trough a street or square, rake with
shot; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>fil</ets> thread.
See <er>File</er> a row.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A line or straight
passage, or the position of that which lies in a straight line.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A firing in the direction of the
length of a trench, or a line of parapet or troops, etc.; a raking
fire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enfilade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Enfilade
<hw>En`fi*lade"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Enfiladed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Enfilading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To pierce,
scour, or rake with shot in the direction of the length of, as a work,
or a line of troops.</def> <rj><au>Campbell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enfiled</ent>⟦br⟧
